<br>
Gwion's Go-on-and-taste-it-before-you-make-snotty-remarks Vegan Chili<br>
<br>
brown lentils (one cup for some, two cups for a lot, three cups for &quot;every vegan I know is coming for dinner&quot;)<br>
one onion (or two if you like onions)<br>
fresh garlic (I use a lot, but you don't have to)<br>
FRESH okra (don't use canned, leave it out otherwise or use broccoli or something)<br>
three or four or five reasonable tomatoes (if it's tomato season, otherwise use a little can of tomato paste)<br>
olive oil<br>
cayenne<br>
tabasco<br>
cumin<br>
chili powder<br>
white sugar (cause honey isn't vegan)<br>
<br>
Chop the onion(s) and garlic and sautee them in olive oil in the bottom of a stockpot.  Use a lot of olive oil because it's gonna be the stock.  Add the lentils -- lentils are cool because unlike beans, you don't have to soak them overnight.  Add water -- two cups of water to one cup of dry lentils.  Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer until the lentils are a ways from done.  <br>
<br>
While the lentils are cooking, get another pan and sautee the cut-up okra in more olive oil -- this somehow keeps it from getting slimy.  Don't worry about it for now because you're not going to add it until later.<br>
<br>
When the lentils are at the &quot;OK, about ten more minutes&quot; stage, dice the tomatoes and throw them in.  Also throw in the cumin, chili powder, and cayenne -- as much as you want.  I always make this really hot because vegan food is kind of blah otherwise.  Also at this stage, if it's too watery-tasting you can add a little more olive oil if you want.  Just throw it in there.<br>
<br>
Then add the Tabasco.  Again, as much as you want, but I always end up using a couple of tablespoons.  Give it a minute for the vinegar to burn off, then taste it.  If you want to scream, it's about right.  Now for the sugar.  Not too much.  Usually about a tablespoon for a medium-sized potful.  The sugar somehow keeps the whole thing from tasting like battery acid &lt;shrug&gt;<br>
<br>
Finally, when it's just going to simmer for a few more minutes to blend the flavors, add the okra.  You can also add kidney beans; I prefer the large red canned ones to the dry ones and if you feel guilty you can always recycle the can.<br>
<br>
I know it sounds totally gross if you are used to regular chili, BUT.  This has no cholesterol, not too much fat, lots of fiber, and lots of protein, and it doesn't taste like cardboard.  The lentils kind of substitute for ground beef, I guess.  In any case, this stuff kept me alive for four years while I went to college, so I know it can't be all bad <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Also, if you're not an actual vegan (meaning, if you eat eggs, which I do), you can bake the leftovers in a casserole with Jiffy corn muffin mix on top.  Mmm...<br>
