<br>
Portobello mushrooms are enormous, about 5&quot; across on average and conveniently round -- like a hamburger bun.  Break the stems off a couple of good sized ones, then brush the caps with olive oil and salt (and anything else you like) and grill outdoors.<br>
<br>
Indoors, cook the caps in about a half inch of water in a skillet.  Add balsamic vinegar, salt, and olive oil to the water before adding the mushrooms.<br>
<br>
Serve like a hamburger.  A good extra for this is a roasted red pepper -- cut a red pepper in half, scoop the seeds out, flatten each half, brush with olive oil and salt, grill outdoors on a grill or indoors in your oven broiler.<br>
<br>
Aganitte, a dyed-in-the-wool meat eater, was mightily skeptical about whether a portobello burger would be at all tasty or satisfying -- but he's now converted.  For mushrooms, these things are awfully meaty.  Kind of hard to describe, I guess, you just have to taste one.<br>
<br>
We have ours with avocado, kosher muenster (fake variety available for actual vegans), lettuce, tomato, and onion on toasted rounds of foccacia.  If there isn't a decent italian bakery nearby, any old bread will do -- the vegan restaurant down the street serves theirs on large potato rolls <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Mmm, I just had one... Mmmm... <p><font color=green face="ARIAL, HELVETICA, LUCIDA SANS"><B>Gwion Llewellyn</B></font><BR> Level, um, 36<BR> Bakin' my way to fish roll heaven!<BR>
